article.description:
Tim Duncan scored 23 points and grabbed 11 rebounds to lead the San Antonio Spurs to their 12th straight win,
an 89-79 victory over the Miami Heat.
article.headline: Duncan leads charge with 23 points, 11 boards

images.name: Duncan, Tim 020323 inline
images.caption: Tim Duncan had his league-leading 55th double-double.

article.linkText: Spurs beat the Heat, win 12th straight
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The way things have gone lately for the San Antonio Spurs lately, they can handle any game plan an opponent throws at them. Just two days after beating Dallas, the team with the league's best offense and worst defense, the Spurs earned their 12th straight victory by beating the Miami Heat 89-79 Saturday night. "Another game, another win," said Tim Duncan, who led the Spurs with 23 points and 11 rebounds. "We've got a great streak going here." The Heat's league-worst offense was no match for San Antonio's defense, which held the Heat to 41-percent shooting. Miami, beaten at home by Indiana on Friday night, trails the Pacers by four games for the Eastern Conference's eighth and final playoff spot. "We're not getting the energy we need from our team at all right now," Heat coach Pat Riley said. "Every time I went back to our starters we lost momentum." Five Spurs scored in double figures, and San Antonio went on a 16-6 run to end the third quarter and take command. Duncan started the run with a dunk after receiving a tip-pass from David Robinson. Spurs guard Tony Parker hit a banking 15-footer that fell just as the shot clock expired and followed it up with a steal and layup to give San Antonio a 71-58 lead heading to the final period. The Spurs led by double figures the rest of the way. "I'm very superstitious," Spurs guard Antonio Daniels said. "I'm not changing anything about my daily routine until we lose." San Antonio used a 13-5 run late in the first half to take a 44-36 lead at the break. Duncan had six points during the surge, which was capped when Parker fed Bruce Bowen with a fastbreak pass he converted into a dunk. San Antonio led 23-14 early in the second quarter, but Miami countered. Three-pointers by Jim Jackson and Eddie Jones, and six points from Eddie House and four more from Alonzo Mourning brought the Heat within 33-31 with 3:57 left in the first half. Jackson led Miami with 17 points. Mourning had 16 points and 11 rebounds. Robinson added 11 points and 10 rebounds for the Spurs. Game notes
Spurs guard Steve Smith missed his third straight game because of a sprained right ankle. San Antonio remained tied with Dallas atop the Midwest Division. ... San Antonio guard Terry Porter played one minute in the first quarter before straining his right calf muscle. He didn't return. ... Duncan had his league-leading 55th double-double.
